<div id="review_3145559650" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3145559650" />
    <a title="Goatboy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35178006-goatboy"><img alt="Goatboy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1558106346p2/35178006.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3145559650?book_show_action=true">Mar 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Goatboy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Goatboy" href="/user/show/35178006-goatboy">Goatboy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3145559650" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1185373027862902038">Having a hard time even knowing how to start this review. Just finished this novel - the first by Krasznahorkai that I’ve read - and it’s like a bomb went off somewhere deep inside me. <br/><br/>Let’s start with Krasznahorkai’s writing style and sentence structure which from page one feels like a slightly drunk out of breath Hungarian coming up to you, grabbing you by your lapels, and dragging you off down the street while immediately starting to say - as if already in the middle of a breathless sentence </span>
  <span id="freeText1185373027862902038" style="display:none">Having a hard time even knowing how to start this review. Just finished this novel - the first by Krasznahorkai that I’ve read - and it’s like a bomb went off somewhere deep inside me. <br /><br />Let’s start with Krasznahorkai’s writing style and sentence structure which from page one feels like a slightly drunk out of breath Hungarian coming up to you, grabbing you by your lapels, and dragging you off down the street while immediately starting to say - as if already in the middle of a breathless sentence - yes, well, as to that I have something to show you, come along come along... There is no choice but to follow as you race through pages and pages of sentences and thoughts, interior monologue making transparent the deepest recesses of people’s psyches and motivations, minor narrative plot points containing infinite realms of consciousness and doubt and philosophy and "what does it all mean and where is it all going?".<br /><br />Although published in 1989, its main theme seems to me to be much older. That is: What does the world look like once God is Dead? What is left? What fills the horrible vacuum that becomes unavoidable, even when that vacuum hides under frozen trash and waste on the streets and wanders those same streets dressed up as feral cats no longer afraid of you or anyone? One answer Krasznahorkai provides here seems to be raw naked power and will, along with the material decay that is ever inescapable. Sure there are signs of beautiful moments and off ramps, possibilities that could be followed. But inevitably, as Krasznahorkai shows, these magically delicate moments of respite and beauty will be trampled over by the crushing boots of a nameless progress. A movement without face grinding ever forward until not even the dead can rest in peace.<br /><br />For those interested, the friend who recommended this to me sent me a link to a very well written review of Krasznahorkai’s latest novel which can be found here: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.themonthly.com.au/blog/adam-rivett/2020/13/2020/1584057091/make-em-laugh-baron-wenckheim-s-homecoming">https://www.themonthly.com.au/blog/ad...</a><br /><br />I know I will read his latest novel in the same way I know I will go back and read all his older novels, for Krasznahorkai created an itch inside me that I truly believe only he will be able to scratch.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1185373027862902038" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


