<div id="review_706669058" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/706669058" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18266379-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1638284277p2/18266379.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/706669058?book_show_action=true">Nov 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/18266379-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18266379-michael?shelf=hungarian-lit">hungarian-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18266379-michael?shelf=krasznahorkai">krasznahorkai</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer706669058" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8029788519019422005">A few reflections on THE MELANCHOLY OF RESISTANCE -<br/><br/>The opening page sets the linquistic table of this universe: &apos;obsolete and unreliable&apos;, &apos;indifference and helpless resignation&apos;, ever-spreading all-consuming chaos&apos;, &apos;future unpredictable&apos;, &apos;the past unrecallable&apos;, &apos;life so haphazard&apos;, &apos;symptoms of disintegration&apos;, &apos;pointless struggle&apos;. 3<br/><br/>A nameless Hungarian town, probably a failed communist collective, decaying, overrun by cats, the populace gripped with a <i>&apos;hysterical sense of foreboding.&apos;</i> 158<br/><br/>C</span>
  <span id="freeText8029788519019422005" style="display:none">A few reflections on THE MELANCHOLY OF RESISTANCE -<br /><br />The opening page sets the linquistic table of this universe: 'obsolete and unreliable', 'indifference and helpless resignation', ever-spreading all-consuming chaos', 'future unpredictable', 'the past unrecallable', 'life so haphazard', 'symptoms of disintegration', 'pointless struggle'. 3<br /><br />A nameless Hungarian town, probably a failed communist collective, decaying, overrun by cats, the populace gripped with a <i>'hysterical sense of foreboding.'</i> 158<br /><br />Classic Krasznahorkai.<br /><br />The mammoth carcass of a sperm whale, wheeled to the center of town by a bizarre circus, the harbinger of a night of anarchy and terror. The image that will remain – only the beginning. The seeds of the town's destruction were already there, hidden among some of its citizens, especially the evil Mrs. Eszter, but it was the nameless 'others,' the 'fur caps and boots,' the thuggish circus followers that carried out the mayhem. Who lit the fuse? Was it The Prince, mysterious member of the Circus? <br /><br />Entropy: dissolution, deterioration – through the novel we are led along a continuum of increasingly smaller systems of entropy, from Valuska's evaporating infinite cosmos, to the apocalyptic night in the unnamed Hungarian town, and lastly to the dissolution of the body itself in the final pages. Physical entropy. And a sort of mental entropy, as slow-witted Valuska's joyful wonder at the universe is shaken, and dissolves away:<i> “now the scales, which had grown ever larger, ever darker with years of looking at things the wrong way, had fallen from his eyes for ever, he knew himself disillusioned, free of the false comforts to which his dimwittedness had deservedly condemned him by hiding 'the true nature of reality' from him.”</i><br />­<br />Krasznahorkai's signature stream of words, free of pauses and paragraphs – the solid block of black ink on each successive page [a “typographic lava flow” one critic called it] – pulls you in and holds you there, for there is no break, no way out.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8029788519019422005" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
